John Edward: “Language proficiency is an essential skill for the citizens of the world”
Scotland’s independent schools broke records for academic achievement in 2018 and once again demonstrated outstanding exam results, which were further enhanced by individual and collective achievements in sports, art, music and other community merits.
With a total of more than 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), aim to provide the highest possible level of service to their students and their parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare their students for further and higher education, for their chosen careers and to be global citizens.
Working in the education sector, which is able to design and implement the planned school curriculum, we can see that modern languages continue to be popular and willingly choose them in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you can talk to a man in a language he understands, he will understand you with his mind.
If you speak to him in his own language, you will speak to his heart.”
This is a strong reminder that we cannot rely solely on English if we want to build relationships and build trust with people from other countries.
According to the results of this year’s exams, we can say that languages are at the peak of popularity and have the best retention ratings in independent schools.
In total, 68 percent of foreign language learners received the highest A rating.
Data collected from 74 schools that are members of SCIS showed that 72 percent of students received the highest A grade in the Mandarin language exam, 72 percent of those who learned German, and 69 percent of those who learned French and 63 percent of those who learned Spanish received the highest A grade.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland see foreign language skills as an essential skill that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages as an elective are now as important as basic subjects (Science, Technology, Engineering and Mathematics) in independent school curricula and elsewhere.
A 2014 survey by the UK Commission for Employment and Skills found that of all the reasons that made it difficult for employers to fill jobs, 17% lacked language skills.
As a result, language skills are becoming increasingly necessary to prepare young people for their future careers.
As the future employability will depend heavily on languages, these skills are becoming essential in a globalised world.
No matter what career a person chooses to pursue with a second language, he or she will be much better off than others in the future if he or she has these lifelong skills.
By being able to communicate directly with people from abroad, a person who speaks several languages will be much more competitive.
According to a 2013 YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults in the UK, 75 percent were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to be interviewed, and French was the only language spoken by a double-digit percentage of people, i.e. 15 percent.
That’s why investing in language learning is important for today’s children.
Several languages, especially in developing countries, will improve children's chances of meaningful employment.
In Scotland, each school is different according to the languages it teaches.
Many schools focus on more classical modern languages, while others teach languages considered to be most important to the UK in view of the future of 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child’s interests may be, there will always be many languages to choose from in an independent school with teaching staff and specialists in the field.
Scotland’s independent schools are ready to create a teaching environment that will prepare children and equip them with the skills they need to live in the future.
It is undeniable that in today’s global business environment, languages remain vital to the country’s future, and this must be reflected in the education system as well.
Indeed, modern languages should definitely be considered as “international communication skills”.
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and outcomes to Scottish youth.
This must be done.
John Edward is the Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
