North Korea says it will not unilaterally disarm without confidence
North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that continued sanctions had deepened their mistrust of the United States and that under such circumstances the country would not unilaterally renounce nuclear weapons.
Ri told the General Assembly that North Korea had taken "significant measures of good will" over the past year, including halting nuclear missile tests, dismantling a nuclear test site, and committing to non-proliferation of nuclear weapons and technology.
"But we have not received a similar response from the US," he said.
“Without any confidence in the United States, we will not be able to trust our national security, and under such circumstances, we will by no means be the first to unilaterally disarm.”
While Ri reiterated North Korea’s complaints about Washington’s opposition to a step-by-step approach to nuclear disarmament that rewards North Korea by step-by-step action, his statement was different in that he did not completely reject the idea of bilateral disarmament, as Pyongyang had done before.
Ri hinted at a joint statement by Kim and Donald Trump at the first meeting between the US president and the North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, when Kim pledged to work on "disarmament of the Korean peninsula" and Trump pledged to ensure North Korea's security.
North Korea is seeking a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States says Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also refused to ease tough international sanctions on North Korea.
“The United States demands nuclear disarmament first and is stepping up the pressure with sanctions to achieve its goal by coercive methods, even renouncing the declaration of the end of the war,” Ri said.
“To think that sanctions can bring us to our knees is like pursuing utopian dreams for people who don’t care.
But the problem is that the continued sanctions are exacerbating our mistrust."
Ri did not mention plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump, which was highlighted by the US leader at the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, he emphasised three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months: "If South Korea were the next country on this nuclear disarmament issue rather than the US, the issue of nuclear disarmament on the Korean peninsula would not have reached such a dead end."
However, Ri’s tone of speech changed dramatically compared to last year when he told the UN General Assembly that when “Mr. Evil President” Trump called Kim a “rocket lord” preparing a suicide mission, it was absolutely inevitable to direct North Korean missiles to the United States.
This year at the United Nations, Trump, who last year threatened to “completely destroy” North Korea, praised Kim for his courage to take steps toward disarmament, but said there was still a long way to go and that sanctions must remain until North Korea met its nuclear disarmament requirements.
On Wednesday, Trump said he had no timetable for this, saying "if it takes two years, three years or five months, it doesn't matter."
China and Russia said the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for its actions.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pomeo told the UN Security Council on Thursday that “the Security Council’s sanctions must be resolutely continued without any concessions until there is complete and definitive, proven nuclear disarmament.”
The Security Council has unanimously approved sanctions against North Korea since 2006 to prevent funding for Pyongyang's nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met Ri behind the scenes at the UN General Assembly and later said he would visit Pyongyang again next month to unleash the soil for the next meeting.
