Harvard students learn enough to rest
A new course at Harvard University this year encouraged all of its students to sleep more to fight a growing macho culture in studios, consuming caffeine and staying awake at night.
One academic found that in the best university in the world, students often do not even have the basic knowledge to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School, and Brigham City, a specialist in women’s hospitals, have prepared a course that he says is the first of its kind in the United States.
Inspiration to prepare this course came to him after talking about the effects of lack of sleep on learning.
“At the end of the talk, a girl came up to me and said, ‘Why am I only being told about this now, in the final year of my studies?’
She said no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep, which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course is offered for the first time this year. It explains how the most important quality sleep habits help to achieve academic and sports results and improve overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s health services department, said the university had decided to offer the course after it became clear that students were suffering from severe sleep deprivation during the week.
The hour-long course includes a series of interactive exercises.
One section contains a dormitory room photo where students can click on a cup of coffee, curtains, simulators, and books to learn about the effects of caffeine, light, how sleep deprivation affects athletic performance, and how important sleep routines are.
In the next section, participants learn how long-term sleep deprivation can increase their risk of heart attacks, strokes, depression and cancer.
Student campus map with interactive icons that encourage participants to reflect on their daily routine.
“We understand that this will not change the behavior of the students.
But we think they have a right to know – just as you have a right to know about the health consequences of choosing to smoke,” Professor Czeisler explained.
The culture of pride to not sleep overnight, he said, still exists. Modern technology and increasing pressure on students have led to the growing problem of sleep deprivation.
“Ensuring students get enough and quality sleep should be their secret weapon in fighting stress, exhaustion, and anxiety,” he said, “even avoiding gaining weight because lack of sleep switches the brain to fasting, so students are constantly hungry.”
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian who studies chemical and physical biology, helped prepare Professor Czeisler's course when he attended one of his courses last year, his first year at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to ask for a course accessible to the entire campus.
It hopes that the next step will be to invite all postgraduate students to take this course before enrolling in this competitive institution.
Professor Czeisler recommended that students set an alarm when it’s time to go to sleep, just like when getting up, and beware of the harmful effects of blue light from electronic devices and LED lights, as they can knock your circadian rhythm out of balance, which can make it difficult to fall asleep.
